								<!-- bodycontent -->
				<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><div class="dablink">For the video game, see <a href="History_of_Biology_(video_game)" title="History of Biology (video game)">History of Biology (video game)</a>.</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:282px;"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Erasmus_Darwin_Temple_of_Nature.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a4/Erasmus_Darwin_Temple_of_Nature.jpg/280px-Erasmus_Darwin_Temple_of_Nature.jpg" width="280" height="412" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a4/Erasmus_Darwin_Temple_of_Nature.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a4/Erasmus_Darwin_Temple_of_Nature.jpg 2x" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Erasmus_Darwin_Temple_of_Nature.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="http://bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
The frontispiece to <a href="Erasmus_Darwin" title="Erasmus Darwin">Erasmus Darwin</a>'s <a href="Evolution" title="Evolution">evolution</a>-themed poem <i>The Temple of Nature</i> shows a goddess pulling back the veil from nature (in the person of <a href="Artemis" title="Artemis">Artemis</a>). Allegory and metaphor have often played an important role in the history of biology.</div>
</div>
</div>
